liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Rising petrol prices were a key factor in the September inflation figure being higher than economists had expected â€” but that was based on fuel prices before the Israel-Gaza war started earlier this month. Oil prices have been rising as a result of the war, but AMP deputy chief economist Diana Mousina says they haven't increased too significantly just yet, so there is a possibility petrol prices could remain at their current (but still elevated) levels. Ms Mousina still expects some prices will continue to come down in the coming months, and says "we will be surprised at how far inflation can fall" next year as Australia braces for softer economic growth. liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Treasurer Jim Chalmers says today's inflation data reflects the global economic experience â€” that although it is moderating, it is proving to be more persistent. Speaking in Canberra about the figures, Mr Chalmers said the 1.2% September increase was consistent with Treasury forecasts, but warned further volatility in inflation is likely in coming months in response to oil markets and fuel prices. "Production cuts and disruptions in global oil markets are a key driver of inflation in the global economy and here at home, with Australians facing higher fuel prices at the bowser," he said. "Petrol prices increased 7.2% in the [September] quarter, contributing a quarter of a percentage point to quarterly inflation. "We shouldn't be surprised to see some volatility in inflation figures going forward, particularly given the global uncertainty from the conflict in the Middle East and the war in Ukraine. "We understand that inflation and higher interest rates that are already in the system are biting households hard and we're acting to make things a little easier."

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: If you're after another hot take on inflation, you're in the right place. My colleague, senior business correspondent Peter Ryan told The World Today that there's no two ways about it â€” these inflation numbers will be a big concern for the RBA board. "That's because while the pace of inflation seems to be slowing, it's not slowing fast enough â€” it's still higher than expected at 5.4% over the year and lower than 6% in the last quarter â€” but still well above the 2 to 3% target where the RBA eventually wants it," he said.
